as an aside it's extremely funny to me that the literal most accurate application of anna tsing's "salvage economies" that I've found is fucking esports lmao

what starts as meeting of hobbyists (people at locals) and/or a "pilgrimage" to holy site (evo/cb) ends up being totally alienated from the experiences of the players and turned into pure viewer statistics for amazon and nothing more - this is not an owner/worker relationship

so any esports money-making operation is constantly attempting to vampirize existing mature communities (see: melee, recent mvc2, unist to an extent) or totally leach/kill the newest target they can manage to get their hands on or produce, potentially killing everything (marvel)

there's no way to totally maximize/extract profits from a game or scene because the more is invested the less sustainable the operation is and the most stable bases are the games that grew for years with zero investment - esports is a salvaging of what value is naturally present

it's truly "renewable" as in if a company totally cuts off support for a game, some will naturally keep playing and the community will and can even experience growth afterwards if the groundwork/environment is rich enough (which paradoxically inversely correlates with esports $$)

they're only "semi" renewable because while new players do naturally begin to pick up fighting games and old players play new ones, there's no way to "factory farm" tournament entrants that can be sustained for more than a couple years (see: early sfv/tekken7/dbfz numbers vs now)

moving this to its own thread: players in the fgc aren't "workers", they're akin to a semi-renewable natural resource since since they play without any profit motive (and those that do profit didn't start out that way), thus all value is dependent on the existence of the resource https://t.co/0zgwYKWXGa

fighting game tournaments (and thus fgc esports) are inherently salvage operations from a non-scalable field of participants, you can't keep the extractive esports superstructure while entirely replacing the real producers of value (players) b/c there's simply no replacements

another day on fgc twitter where someone is making fun of numpad notation while actively refusing to learn when people bend over backwards to explain it in their replies

@spacetwinks @MasterWholigans i'm mainly saying all this because I was also overwhelmed at first but as soon as I started mentally replacing each number with a direction rather than memorizing each number string as a specific "motion" the entire thing made sense

@spacetwinks @MasterWholigans you're looking at the ascii characters for numbers and realizing each individual character represents something you already know

I think the most common mental block is looking at it and thinking "that's a big number" when in reality there's no "number" just direction characters

@spacetwinks @MasterWholigans S-SE-E has the same "meaning" as 236, our brains try to make a shorthand that 236 itself is a "word" that has meaning but really it's a collection of directions that could be accomplished by any other labeling system

you could replace numbers with arrow emojis and mean the same

@spacetwinks @MasterWholigans you can read through the notation character by character and replace each number you see with a direction without having to know anything a priori outside of the numpad

the numbers aren't "words" , you could replace them with compass directions and the result would be the same

@spacetwinks @MasterWholigans you don't need to do point-to-point rote memorization in order to translate sf notation to numpad, you don't need to memorize that 236 = qcf etc

when you're reading combo notation you basically just need to translate the numpad to directions so that 236 is ⬇️↘️➡️

@spacetwinks @MasterWholigans american street fighting notation is essentially a language-like collection of words, "qcf" is an abbreviation of other words that represent a concept so you need to "learn the language" to figure out which words go with which concepts of stick motion

@spacetwinks @MasterWholigans like I learned more about english grammar (as a native english speaker) learning various french tenses than I did in english classes, english is just a messy language that tries to use the same helper words too many times to describe different verb states

@spacetwinks @MasterWholigans lol imo french grammar outside of having to know atypical verbs is more systemic/coherent than english, like "j'mappelle" is just a reflexive verb with yourself as the subject saying that "I call myself" rather than having to reference the abstract concept of "a name" in english

@spacetwinks @MasterWholigans oh the other thing is that numpad notation is transferrable across languages since you don't have to know abbreviations

real handy in kof because there's no standard abbreviation for "qcb then hcf" that holds between english and jp/chinese while 2141236 is long but intelligible
@spacetwinks @MasterWholigans numbers are just ascii characters like anything else, you don't need to operate on them just read them in the order they're on the screen

@spacetwinks @MasterWholigans eh it's not something that you necessarily need to be able to "fluently" be able to read right off the bat and you can pick out the little chunks that make sense to you to piece the entire combo together, eg if something starts with a 2 you know it's probably gonna be a qc motion

@spacetwinks @MasterWholigans using abbreviations is more helpful for initial learning but then after a certain point numpad notation is simply superior (command normals, unusual motions, having to describe different types of TKs, 8way airdashes etc)

@spacetwinks @MasterWholigans imo I think that a better analogy for numpad notation is algebraic chess notation, it's not something that's chosen because it's immediately/intuitively comprehensible but because it's the most efficient way to describe things with the least ambiguity
